		<b>Comment By Fairlee Winfield, 11-06-08</b>
		<p>I'd like to know more about "Words to Stir the Soul."  I am interested in the literature of immigation but have trouble finding authors.  Is there means of finding out which authors the readers have selected for their short selections?  <br />
<br />
Thanks,<br />
<br />
Fairlee Winfield<br />
Author of BUFFALOED</p>
		
		<b>Comment By Jenny Shank, 11-06-08</b>
		<p>Hi Fairlee,<br />
<br />
I will check with the Center for the American West and see what I can find out.</p>
		
		<b>Comment By Fairlee Winfield, 11-06-08</b>
		<p>Thanks Jenny,<br />
<br />
I'll look forward to hearing something more about the interesting topic.</p>
		
		<b>Comment By Shawna, 11-07-08</b>
		<p>Hey Fairlee,<br />
<br />
We don't have a complete list of authors that our readers have chosen yet, but as soon as we get that, we can send it your way.  Once we finish the programs, we'll send you a .pdf which includes each reader and which book they will be reading from.<br />
<br />
Have a good one!<br />
<br />
Shawna<br />
Marketing Assistant and<br />
Website Administrator<br />
Center of the American West<br />
<a href="http://www.newwest.net/?URL=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.centerwest.org">http://www.centerwest.org</a></p>
		
		<b>Comment By Fairlee Winfield, 11-07-08</b>
		<p>Thanks Shawna.  I'll be looking forward to it.  My novel's main character is a Norwegian girl in 1904 Montana.  Writing it has increased my interest in the immigrant experience.  I believe that so far we've heard mainly superficial and jingoistic representations and need to dig a little deeper.<br />
<br />
Thanks again, sincerely,<br />
<br />
Fairlee Winfield<br />
Author of BUFFALOed<br />
<a href="http://www.newwest.net/?URL=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.fairleewinfield.com">http://www.fairleewinfield.com</a><br />
